Chinese Stocks in the U.S.: Cnooc, PetroChina, Sina, Sinopec

-- B y   B e l i n d a   C a o
-- 
2011-09-21T21:35:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-21/chinese-stocks-in-the-u-s-cnooc-petrochina-sina-sinopec.html
The Bank of New York Mellon  China 
ADR Index, which tracks American depositary receipts, fell 3.5
percent to 369.67, the lowest since July 2010. The New York
Stock Exchange China Index declined 3.3 percent to 223.05. The
Shanghai Composite Index gained 2.7 percent to 2,512.96.  The following companies were among the most active Chinese
shares in New York trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are as of the close of trading at 4 p.m. New York time.  China will levy a tax on resources based on their value and
volume, according to a statement on the government’s website,
citing a decision from a cabinet meeting presided over by
Premier  Wen Jiabao . The country will adjust tax ratios on crude
oil and natural gas exploration, yesterday’s statement said,
without giving details.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  , China’s largest offshore energy
producer, slumped 5.9 percent to $158.88, the lowest level since
July 2010.  PetroChina Co. (PTR US) the nation’s biggest oil producer,
sank 4.7 percent to $115.98, the lowest in almost a year.  China Petroleum and Chemical Corp. (SNP US), the country’s
biggest refiner known as Sinopec, slid 4.2 percent, the most in
more than a month, to $93.50.  Sina Corp. (SINA US), the owner of China’s third-most
visited website and the Twitter-like Weibo service, slipped 3
percent to a six-week low of $90.02. Speculation yesterday that
the government issued licenses to four microblog service
providers, and that Sina didn’t get one, were “pure rumors,”
Sina said in a message to all its Weibo users today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Belinda Cao in New York at 
